In React, "props" is short for properties, which are a way to pass data from a parent 
component to a child component. Props are read-only and cannot be modified by the child 
component.

Props are passed to a component as an object, and can contain any data, including strings,
 numbers, arrays, and even other components. The child component can then use the props 
 to render its output.

Here s an example of passing props to a child component:

 
// Parent component
import React from 'react';
import ChildComponent from './ChildComponent';

function ParentComponent() {
  return (
    <div>
      <h1>Hello, world!</h1>
      <ChildComponent name="John" age={30} />
    </div>
  );
}

export default ParentComponent;

// Child component
import React from 'react';

function ChildComponent(props) {
  return (
    <div>
      <p>My name is {props.name}.</p>
      <p>I am {props.age} years old.</p>
    </div>
  );
}

export default ChildComponent;
In the example above, the parent component ParentComponent is passing two props, name and
 age, to the child component ChildComponent. The child component then receives the props 
 as an object in its function parameters, and uses them to render its output.
